{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638117"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:49:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:49:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17688"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17688"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10402"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72058"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10402"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17688"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57528"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10460"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24313"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24348"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72058"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vestibular system contains specialised structures that help maintain balance and spatial orientation. The semicircular canals play a crucial role in detecting head movements.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the response of the semicircular canals during sustained constant velocity rotation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continuous deflection of the cupula","Immediate cessation of hair cell firing","Oscillating sensations of movement","Initial sensation of movement followed by no sensation","Progressively increasing sensation of movement"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring sustained constant velocity rotation, there is an \u003Cstrong\u003Einitial sensation of movement followed by no sensation\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs because the cupula initially deflects due to inertia of the endolymph, but then returns to its resting position as the endolymph catches up to the rotation speed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous deflection of the cupula\u003C/strong\u003E occurs initially but the cupula gradually returns to its neutral position during constant velocity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgressively increasing sensation of movement\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the sensation actually decreases to zero over time as the cupula returns to its resting position.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate cessation of hair cell firing\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur as hair cells maintain their baseline firing rate during constant velocity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOscillating sensations of movement\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the sensation steadily decreases rather than oscillating back and forth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis phenomenon explains why we do not feel continuous movement during steady flight in an aeroplane, but can detect changes in velocity or direction. When rotation stops, the endolymph continues moving briefly, creating a false sensation of rotation in the opposite direction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The semicircular canals detect angular acceleration of the head through movement of endolymph fluid.","At rest, hair cells in the ampulla maintain a baseline firing rate due to slight bending of their stereocilia.","The cupula returns to its resting position during constant velocity rotation, resulting in no sensation of movement."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57528"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17688"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57528"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T22:10:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:11:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10402"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72058"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"upd